{
  "answer": "**The *Bṛhaspati Smṛti* (Chapter 1) enumerates twelve kinds of witnesses among the means of proof in legal proceedings.**[^1]\n\nIt describes the \"concealed witness\" (*gūḍhasākṣin*) in these terms:\n\n> He who, concealed by a wall, is made to hear a statement about a debt,  \n> and who, when it is denied, relates it as it happened, is called a concealed witness.  \n> // Brh_1,5.8 //[^2]\n\nThis is one category in a list that includes subscribed witnesses, recorded witnesses, reminded witnesses, kinsmen, messengers, chance witnesses, secondary witnesses, and others (twelve total).[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-c9cb41](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-c9cb41).\n[^2]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-2ee353](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-2ee353).\n[^3]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-0cc2ab](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-0cc2ab).",
